---
title: Chicken Katsu with Sesame Roasted Broccoli & Ginger Rice
description: It’s pretty tough to beat the rich flavor and crispy texture of Japanese katsu. In this riff on the dish, we coat pork chops in sour cream and panko, then shallow-fry them until crunchy and golden brown. Ginger-infused rice and sesame-studded roasted broccoli make the perfect pairing, and tangy, savory-sweet katsu sauce tops every crunchy bite.
image: https://img.hellofresh.com/f_auto,fl_lossy,h_640,q_auto,w_1200/hellofresh_s3/image/6526e7d9bfc560dc00ea4fa6-a5090944.jpeg
pdf: https://www.hellofresh.com/recipecards/card/6526e7d9bfc560dc00ea4fa6.pdf
time required: 35 minutes
cuisine: Asian
nutrition:
  calories: 870 kcal
  fat: 37 g
  saturated fat: 10 g
  carbohydrates: 93 g
  sugar: 12 g
  protein: 43 g
  fiber: 4 g
  sodium: 1380 mg
servings: 2
source: https://www.hellofresh.com/recipes/chicken-katsu-6526e7d9bfc560dc00ea4fa6
author: HelloFresh
course: main course
---

Adjust rack to top position and preheat oven to 425 degrees. Wash and dry produce.

Cut @broccoli florets{8%ounce} into bite-size pieces if necessary. Peel and mince or
grate @ginger{1%thumb}. Trim and thinly slice @scallions{2}, separating whites
from greens.

Toss broccoli on a #baking sheet{} with a large drizzle of @cooking oil{}, @salt{},
and @pepper{}. Roast on top rack until tender, ~{15-20%minutes}.

Once roasted, carefully toss with @sesame seeds{1%tablespoon}.

While broccoli roasts, heat a drizzle of oil in a #small pot{} over medium-high
heat. Add ginger and scallion whites; cook, stirring, until fragrant,
~{1%minute}.

Stir in @jasmine rice{1/2%cup}, @water{3/4%cup}, and a pinch of @salt{}. Bring to
a boil, then cover and reduce heat to low. Cook until rice is tender,
~{15-18%minutes}.

Keep covered off heat until ready to serve.

Meanwhile, pat @chicken cutlets{10%ounce} dry with #paper towels{}; place between
two large pieces of #plastic wrap{}. Pound with a #mallet{} or #rolling pin{} until
pork is about ½-inch thick.

Place @panko breadcrumbs{1%cup}, @garlic powder{1%teaspoon}, salt, and pepper
in a #gallon-size zip-close bag{}.

Place @sour cream{1.5%tablespoon} in a #medium bowl{}; add pork and turn to
evenly coat.

Add coated pork to bag with seasoned panko and seal to close. Shake until pork
is evenly coated.

> TIP: You may need to move around pork chops in bag, pressing with your hands,
> to spread out panko and make it stick.

> Swap in chicken for pork. TIP: If your cutlets are already ½ inch thick,
> you can skip the pounding.

Heat a ¼-inch layer of @cooking oil{} in a large, preferably nonstick,
#pan{} over medium-high heat. Once oil is shimmering and hot enough that a
pinch of panko sizzles when added to pan, add coated pork (discard any
remaining panko in bag).

Cook until panko is golden brown and pork is cooked through,
~{3-5%minutes} per side.

> For 4 servings, cook in batches.

Transfer to a #paper-towel-lined plate{}.

Place @katsu sauce{4%tablespoon} in a #small microwave-safe bowl{}; microwave
until warmed through, ~{30%seconds}.

Fluff rice with a #fork{}; stir in @butter{1%tablespoon} and season with salt and pepper.

Divide rice, pork, and broccoli between plates. Drizzle pork with katsu sauce.
Sprinkle with scallion greens and serve.

> Chicken is fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 165°.